New Rules for the World Economy
CAMBRIDGE, MASS.: Let's assume that the leading politicians of the world would once again meet in Bretton Woods, New Hampshire, to draft a new world economic order.
They would naturally focus primarily on today's problems: the crisis in the Eurozone, global recovery, financial regulation, international macroeconomic imbalances, etc. However, dealing with these issues would force the assembled leaders to go beyond them and reconsider the soundness of overall global economic arrangements.
Here are seven principles based on sound common sense for global economic management, on which they might agree.
(I discuss these in more detail in my new book, The Globalization Paradox.)
1. Markets must be deeply embedded in existing control systems.
The idea that markets can self-regulate has suffered a fatal blow due to the recent financial crisis and should be buried once and for all.
Markets need other societal institutions that support them.
They rely on courts, legal systems, and regulatory bodies that establish and enforce rules.
They depend on the stabilizing functions provided by central banks and countercyclical fiscal policy.
They require the political acceptance generated by redistributive taxation, safety nets, and social insurance.
And all this applies equally to global markets.
2. For the foreseeable future, democratic state leadership is likely to be largely organized within national political communities.
The nation-state lives, even if it may be somewhat faltering, and remains essentially the only game in town.
The pursuit of a world government is a futile love affair.
That national governments would cede significant control to transnational institutions is hardly to be expected; moreover, regulatory harmonization would benefit little societies with differing needs and preferences.
The European Union could be the only exception to this axiom, although its current crisis seems rather to confirm it.
All too often, we waste international cooperation on overly ambitious goals. In the end, the results are weak, representing the smallest common denominator between the major countries.
When international cooperation is "successful," it produces rules that are either toothless or reflect the preferences of the more powerful countries.
The Basel rules on capital requirements and the WTO rules on subsidies, intellectual property, and investment measures typify this kind of excessive ambition.
We can strengthen the efficiency and legitimacy of globalization by supporting democratic procedures in our own country, rather than undermining them.
That national governments would cede significant control to transnational institutions is hardly to be expected; moreover, regulatory harmonization would benefit little societies with differing needs and preferences.
3. Pluralistic Prosperity: The acknowledgment that the central institutional infrastructure of the world economy must be built at the national level gives individual countries the freedom to develop institutions that best meet their needs.
The USA, Europe, and Japan have generated comparable prosperity in the long term.
Yet their labor markets, corporate governance, antitrust regulations, social security systems, and financial systems differ significantly, and a sequence of these "models"—each different in every decade—is then presented as the great success that others should emulate.
The most successful societies of the future will allow room for experiments and permit further evolution of their institutions.
A world economy that recognizes the necessity and value of institutional diversity will foster rather than suppress such experimental openness and evolutionary development.
4. Countries have the right to protect their own rules and institutions.
The aforementioned principles may appear innocuous.
But they carry powerful implications that clash with the prevailing opinion of globalization supporters.
One such implication is the right of individual countries to protect their national institutional decisions.
The recognition of institutional diversity would be meaningless if countries did not have the instruments available to shape and preserve their own institutions—in a word: to "protect" them.
We should therefore accept that countries may retain national rules—tax policy, financial regulation, labor standards, or rules protecting consumer health and safety—and that they are entitled to do so by erecting barriers at their borders if trade demonstrably threatens domestic practices that enjoy widespread public support.
If globalization advocates are right, calls for such protective measures will fail due to a lack of evidence or support.
If they are wrong, there is a safety valve to ensure that conflicting values—those of open economies and those of maintaining national regulations—both receive appropriate attention in public debates.
5. Countries have no right to impose their own institutions on others.
The use of restrictions in cross-border trade or in the financial sector to maintain values and rules in one's own country should not be confused with their use to impose these values and rules on other countries.
The rules of globalization should not force Americans or Europeans to consume goods produced in a way that most citizens in these countries find unacceptable.
Equally, they should not allow the US or the EU to use trade sanctions or other pressure measures to change labor market rules, environmental policies, or financial regulations of other countries.
Countries have a right to difference, not to forced convergence.
Countries have a right to protect their own rules and institutions, and these principles, while appearing innocuous, are important for maintaining sovereignty and adaptability.
6. International economic agreements to regulate the interaction between national institutions: Relying on nation-states to provide the fundamental steering functions of the world economy does not mean that we should abandon international rules.
The Bretton Woods system finally also had clear rules, even if these were limited in scope and depth.
A complete free-for-all would benefit no one.
What we need are traffic rules for the world economy that help vehicles of different sizes, shapes, and speeds to pass each other, rather than prescribing an identical car or a uniform speed limit.
We should strive for a maximum level of globalization that is in harmony with the preservation of space for diversity in national institutional arrangements.
7. Undemocratic countries cannot claim the same rights and privileges within the international economic order as democracies.
What gives the aforementioned principles their attractiveness and legitimacy is that they are based on democratic consultation – where this actually takes place, within the nation-states.
If states are not democratic, this framework collapses.
We can no longer assume that their institutional arrangements reflect the preferences of their citizens.
Therefore, other, less liberal rules must apply for undemocratic states.
These are the principles that the architects of the next global economic order must accept.
Most importantly, they must accept the ultimate paradox illustrated by each of these principles: globalization works best when it is not taken too far.
